      "title": "The Spiritual Architecture of the Word",
      "content": "“For where there is a will, the death of the person who made the will must be recorded. » — Hebrews 9:16-17\n\n1. The Bible: more than a book, a divine building\n\nThe Bible is not an ordinary book. It is a spiritual monument, a celestial architecture.\nBut to understand it, you must not read it like a simple novel. We must discern its interior structure, as we explore a sacred temple.\n\nThe Bible is divided into two main parts:\n    • The Old Testament\n    • The New Testament\n\nThese two parts do not oppose each other, they fulfill each other.\nBut they don't work in the same way.\n\n2. Old and New Covenant: two seasons, one God\n\nIn the Bible, God speaks by covenants.\n\nThe Old Covenant\n    • It was established between God and the people of Israel.\n    • It was based on the Law, given to Moses: commandments, rules, sacrifices to follow to remain in relationship with God.\n    • It was a covenant based on obedience.\n\nThe New Covenant\n    • It was inaugurated by Jesus Christ.\n    • It is based on grace, faith, and the action of the Holy Spirit.\n    • It is an alliance of inner transformation.\n\n3. The spiritual testament: what Hebrews 9 says\n\nThe author of Hebrews uses a very powerful comparison:\n\nA covenant functions like a will.\n\nImagine a will written by a father for his children.\nAs long as the father is alive, the will is not active.\nIt is only upon his death that the inheritance becomes available.\n\nLikewise, the New Covenant came into effect after Jesus' death, not before.\n\nBefore the cross, even though Jesus was already present, the religious system in place was still that of the old covenant.\n\n4. Jesus: the tipping point between the two alliances\n\n“But when the time was fulfilled, God sent his Son, born of woman, born under the law, that he might redeem those who were under the law, that we might receive adoption. » Galatians 4:4-5 \n\nJesus came to the heart of the Old Covenant, to fulfill it, not reject it.\nHe was born under the law, but it was through his death and resurrection that he opened the door to a new covenant.\n\nIt is at the cross that everything changes:\n    • The old system of sacrifices is ended.\n    • The curtain of the Temple is torn.\n    • Access to God becomes personal, free, and direct.\n\n5. Blood: key to both alliances\n\nIn the old covenant:\n    • Priests offered animal blood for temporary forgiveness of sins.\n    • These sacrifices had to be repeated every year.\n\n“For the life of the flesh is in the blood...it is for atonement. » — Leviticus 17:11\n\nIn the new alliance:\n    • Only one blood was shed: that of Jesus Christ.\n    • It was offered once and for all, forever.\n\n“This is my blood… shed for the remission of sins. » — Matthew 26:28\n\nThe blood of Jesus does not cover faults, it erases them.\n\n6. Why understanding structure is essential\n\nIf you read the Bible without understanding this transition between the two covenants, you risk:\n    • Mix the commandments given to Israel with grace in Christ;\n    • Feel crushed by laws that Jesus has already fulfilled;\n    • Missing out on the freedom and new life that God offers today.\n\nUnderstanding structure means walking in right season with God.\n\nSimple example:\n\nAn heir who continues to live like a slave, even though the will is already in force.",
