      "title": "The Path of Light: Principles of Reading",
      "content": "“Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds from the mouth of God. » — Matthew 4:4\n\n1. Strategic reading for a profound revelation\n\nThe Bible is a living book.\nBut it is also spiritual, deep and coded. It doesn't read like a novel.\n\nThis is why it is essential to know where to start, especially when you are new to the faith.\n\n2. Why does the New Testament actually begin in Acts chapter 2?\n\nMany think the New Testament begins at Matthew chapter 1, because that is where the editor placed it in our Bibles.\n\nBut according to biblical revelation, the New Testament does not really begin until Acts chapter 2, for a very specific reason:\nThis is where the New Covenant comes alive.\n\n3. The true birth of the New Testament\n\n“This is the cup of the new covenant in my blood, which is shed for you. » — Luke 22:20\n“After this I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh…” —Joel 2:28\n“For the life of the flesh is in the blood…” — Leviticus 17:11\n\n    A. A classic error: believing that the New Testament begins with Matthew\n\nIn most Bibles, the New Testament page opens at Matthew chapter 1.\nBut according to spiritual revelation and divine command, the New Testament actually begins at Acts chapter 2.\n\nWhy? Because the New Testament is not a publishing title,\nbut a spiritual Covenant, sealed by blood, and accomplished by the Holy Spirit.\n\n    B. Blood marks the beginning of the New Covenant\n\n“This cup is the new covenant in my blood, which is shed for you. » — Luke 22:20\n\nJesus not only says: “Here is the wine”,\nbut: “This is the blood of the New Covenant, which will be shed for you. »\n\nThe word “widespread” is crucial here. It expresses a total act, given, poured, offered.\n\nAnd according to Leviticus 17:11, God had already said:\n\n“For the life of the flesh is in the blood…”\n\nIn other words:\n    • Blood = Life\n\nAnd Jesus also says:\n\n“It is the Spirit who gives life” — John 6:63\nSo:\n\n    • Life = Spirit\n\nIn summary:\n    • Blood = Life = Spirit\n\n    C. Joel's prophecy and its fulfillment in Acts\n\n“After this I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh…” —Joel 2:28\n\nDo you notice? The same word comes back: “I will spread”.\n    • Jesus says: “my blood shed”\n    • God says: “my Spirit poured out”\n\nIt is the same divine act, in two dimensions:\n    - Spilled blood (Luke 22:20)\n    - The Spirit poured out (Joel 2:28 → Acts 2)\n\nAnd it is in Acts chapter 2, at Pentecost, that this word is fulfilled:\n\n“This is what was spoken by the prophet Joel…” — Acts 2:16\n\n    D. The true beginning of the New Testament\n\nThe New Testament, or New Covenant, begins where blood is actually shed, and where life (the Spirit) is shed.\n\nIt is not at the birth of Jesus (Matthew 1),\nit's not at baptism,\nit’s not even at the cross…\n\nIt is at the moment when the blood becomes Spirit,\nat the moment when divine life enters into man through the Spirit,\non the day of Pentecost, in Acts chapter 2.\n\nSpiritual conclusion\n\nThe New Testament is not a printed page.\nIt is a living reality:\n    • Blood spilled = life given\n    • Life given = Spirit sent\n    • The Spirit sent = the regenerated man\n    • The regenerated man = the beginning of the New Covenant\n\nThis is why the true beginning of the New Testament is Acts 2.\n\n4. Where to start reading the Bible?\n\nHere is the common error:\nMany start with the Old Testament, and get lost in images, laws, genealogies...\n\nBut we must start with reality before understanding the shadow.\n\n“The Old Testament is the shadow, the New Testament is the body. »\n\n5. Why start with the New Testament?\n\nBecause:\n    • The Old Testament is a mystery.\n    • The New Testament is the interpretation of the mystery.\n\nYou can't know a person from their shadow.\nBut if you know the person, then you can understand the shadow.\n\nThe Old Testament is the parables.\nThe New Testament is the explanation of the parables.\n\nThe Old Testament is metaphors.\nThe New Testament is its fulfillment and revelation.\n\n6. Recommended reading structure for every believer\n\nHere is the strategic reading order to discover the Word with light and growth:\n    a. The Epistles (Romans to Jude)\nThis is where you discover who you are in Christ, how to live the faith, how to resist, love, walk in the Spirit.\n    b. The Gospels (Matthew, Mark, Luke, John)\nYou meet Jesus. You see God incarnate.\n    c. The Acts of the Apostles\nYou discover how the Church was born, how the Holy Spirit acts in believers.\n    d. The Old Testament (Genesis to Malachi)\nYou understand the promise, the symbols, the figures which announced Christ.\n    e. The Apocalypse (Revelation)\nYou receive the final vision, the glory, the eternal victory, the triumph of the Kingdom.\n\nTo remember:\n    • You don’t start with the shadow.\n    • You start with light.\n    • You don't start with mystery, you start with revelation.\n\nIt is the light of the New Testament that casts the shadow of the Old.\n\nIf you want to grow in truth, start where life begins: with the Spirit.",
