      "title": "The Word: Between the Letter and the Spirit",
      "content": "“For the letter kills, but the Spirit gives life. » —2 Corinthians 3:6\n\n1. The Bible: a unique book… but mysterious\n\nThe Bible is the most read book in human history.\nIt has crossed the centuries, translated into thousands of languages, copied, meditated on, preached in every corner of the world.\n\nBut here is an astonishing truth:\n\nYou can read the Bible without ever meeting God.\n\nYes, you can read its words, know its stories, memorize its verses... without ever experiencing the life it contains.\n\nFor what ? Because the letter alone is not enough.\n\n2. The letter kills: what does it mean?\n\nThe apostle Paul says:\n\n“The letter kills, but the Spirit gives life. »\n\n“The letter”:\n    • These are the words, the laws, the commandments, the written texts in their raw form.\n    • It can be learned intellectually, without inner transformation.\n\n“But the Spirit”:\n    • It is the presence of God that gives life to the text;\n    • It reveals, it enlightens, it makes the heart burn when you read;\n    • It transforms information into living revelation.\n\nWithout the Spirit, the Bible can become a cold religious tool, or even a weapon to judge, condemn, control.\n\n3. The Word is not a magic code\n\nSome believe that the Bible works like a divine code: it would be enough to pronounce a verse for a miracle to happen.\nBut it is not a grimoire or a secret formula.\nIt is a living testimony, a voice that speaks to those who listen with the heart.\n\nThe difference is not in the words, but in the posture of the reader:\n    • A humble heart receives life.\n    • A religious mind is just given rules.\n\n4. The Old Testament: a shadow that announces\n\nIn the Old Testament, God often spoke through:\n    • Symbols (the brazen serpent, the tabernacle, etc.);\n    • Images (the lamb, the manna, the pillar of fire, etc.);\n    • Prophetic gestures (Noah, Moses, David, etc.).\n\nAll of these were shadows, temporary illustrations that pointed to a future reality: Jesus Christ.\n\nWhat was veiled in the Old is revealed in the New.\n\n5. In the New Testament: the veil is lifted\n\nJesus comes to fulfill what the Elder announced.\nHe is:\n    • The Lamb of God;\n    • The bread of life;\n    • The true temple;\n    • The Word made flesh.\n\nAnd it is through the Holy Spirit that all this becomes clear in your heart.\n\n6. The indispensable role of the Holy Spirit\n\nYou can have a library full of Bibles and still never hear from God if the Spirit does not speak to you.\n\nThe Holy Spirit:\n    • Open your spiritual eyes;\n    • Makes the Word personal;\n    • Reveals the depth behind each verse.\n\n“When He comes, the Spirit of truth, He will guide you into all truth.” —John 16:13\n\n7. Read with the Spirit, not just with the eyes\n\nHere is a simple, yet powerful key:\n\nBefore opening your Bible, invoke the Holy Spirit.\n\nJust tell him:\n“Spirit of God, speak to me. Open my heart. Show me Jesus in these pages. »\n\nFor the letter alone can harden you, but the Spirit makes the Word alive, sharp, gentle and powerful.",
